projects.description:
In August 2012, Vice-Chancellor Professor John Dewar established the Radical Learning Project under the leadership of the Senior Deputy Vice-Chancellor Professor John Rosenberg to inform the development of La Trobe’s Strategic Plan.

For a twelve-week period, the purpose of the Radical Learning Project was to:
•	investigate new ideas and approaches from a global perspective that will enhance the quality of learning and teaching at La Trobe;
•	imagine the future of higher education, beyond 2017, and recommend the ways in which La Trobe can position itself to be an edgy, exciting and capable institution;
•	explore the possibilities for improving the quality of student learning, student engagement, flexibility and graduate outcomes;
•	consider the ways in which we define our student experience, the ways in which we make creative use of technology to support it, and the technical and design skills needed to deliver it.

The project ran from September - November 2012, with the purpose of imagining the future of learning higher education, beyond 2017.   The project looked for new ideas, approaches and innovations and was intended to be creative, exploratory and non-judgmental.    The Radical Learning Group scanned the horizon and looked for innovative and creative approaches that will enhance and lift the quality of teaching and learning at La Trobe.

The core Radical Learning Group included: Associate Professor Claire Macken, Director, Flexible and Online Learning Development projects, Associate Professor Kay Souter, Radical Learning Project, Dr Christopher Scanlon, Senior Lecturer, School of Journalism, HUSS, Matthew Riddle, Senior Lecturer (Academic Development), FBEL and Tony Jarvis, Associate Dean (International), HUSS.

profile_positions.description:
The primary objective of this position is to continue to develop and implement the Faculty’s Teaching and Learning Plan and related activities under the guidance of the Associate Dean (Academic) and provide professional development in curriculum, teaching and learning for lecturing and tutorial staff.  Duties and responsibilities include:
•	Deputise for the Associate Dean (Academic);
•	Coordinate, design and deliver workshops, seminars and supporting materials on a wide range of curriculum, teaching and learning issues;
•	Contribute at a high level of competence to University/Faculty/School committees focused on academic/teaching and learning areas;
•	Initiate, lead and participate in internally- and externally-funded research and development projects that focus on teaching and learning issues, and;
•	Conduct research which results in publications in relevant areas and attracts research funding.
